---
/**
 * Keep inline tags on one line with outer spaces (Astro whitespace).
 * Never break before <em>/<strong>/<a> after a word.
 */
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="Parfit: Psychological Continuity and What Matters in Survival | Foundations | Identity Engineering">
	<main class="min-h-screen">
		<section class="border-b border-white/10 px-6 pt-28 pb-16">
			<div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl">
				<a href="/foundations" class="mb-6 inline-block text-sm text-white/40 transition hover:text-white/70">
					← Foundations
				</a>
				<div class="text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">Foundations · Parfit</div>
				<h1 class="mt-3 text-5xl font-bold tracking-tighter leading-[0.95] text-white md:text-6xl">
					Psychological Continuity and What Matters in Survival
				</h1>
				<p class="mt-6 max-w-2xl text-xl font-light leading-relaxed text-white/50">
					A reductionist view in which personal identity is not treated as a deep further fact. In Parfit’s framing, what often matters for survival-oriented concern is psychological continuity and connectedness (Relation R), rather than strict numerical identity alone.
				</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="px-6 py-16">
			<div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl space-y-12 text-lg leading-relaxed text-white/55">
				<div class="rounded-2xl border border-white/10 bg-white/[0.03] p-5 text-base leading-relaxed text-white/60">
					<strong class="text-white/80">Reading protocol on this page:</strong> First Parfit in his own terms. Then inspirations for Identity Engineering. Then additions from Identity Engineering perspective. The purpose here is not to describe Parfit in his full being, but to distill the essential stance relevant to identity and learn from him within this framework. That is not a claim to devalue his work or to say it would be invalid when read on its own terms.
				</div>

				<div>
					<div class="mb-3 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">1 · Reductionism about Personal Identity</div>
					<p>
						In <em class="text-white/75 not-italic">Reasons and Persons</em> (1984) Derek Parfit argues that personal identity is not a deep further fact beyond physical and psychological continuity. In that reductionist frame, what we call personal identity is explained through facts about brains, bodies, and psychological connections.
					</p>
					<p class="mt-4">
						This is a reductionist position: once the relevant physical and psychological facts are fixed, no additional metaphysical ingredient is needed to explain persistence talk.
					</p>
				</div>

				<div>
					<div class="mb-3 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">2 · Psychological Continuity and Relation R</div>
					<div class="mb-4 rounded-xl border border-white/10 bg-black/20 p-4 text-sm text-white/60">
						<strong class="text-white/80">Core claim (Parfit):</strong> What matters for survival, responsibility, and ethics is not strict personal identity but <strong class="text-white/80">Relation R</strong>: psychological connectedness and continuity (overlapping chains of memory, intention, belief, character, etc.) with the right kind of cause.
					</div>
					<p>
						Through thought experiments (teletransportation, fission cases, brain transplants), Parfit argues that Relation R can come apart from strict numerical identity. In fission cases, for example, one person can stand in strong psychological continuity relations to two future persons; neither is straightforwardly numerically identical with the original, yet both preserve key continuity features.
					</p>
					<p class="mt-4">
						Parfit’s practical upshot is that concern may track the quality and richness of psychological connections over time, not identity considered in isolation.
					</p>
				</div>

				<div>
					<div class="mb-3 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">3 · Relevance for Identity Engineering</div>
					<div class="mb-4 rounded-xl border border-cyan-400/20 bg-cyan-400/[0.04] p-4 text-sm text-white/65">
						<strong class="text-white/80">Inspiration from Parfit:</strong> personal identity is not treated as a fixed metaphysical given. Practical concern can be reframed around maintenance and extension of psychological continuity and connectedness.
					</div>
					<div class="mb-4 rounded-xl border border-violet-400/20 bg-violet-400/[0.04] p-4 text-sm text-white/65">
						<strong class="text-white/80">IE additions:</strong> Relation R interpreted as a psychological substrate for Identity Stem continuity; branching cases used as models for extending identity geometry into multiple trajectories; and a shift from “same person” to “what matters” as a design-oriented framing.
					</div>
					<ul class="space-y-4">
						<li>
							<strong class="text-white/80">Relation R as extended Stem:</strong> The Stem is not a fixed inner core but the ongoing chain of psychological connections. Identity Engineering is the deliberate work of strengthening, extending, and curving these connections over time.
						</li>
						<li>
							<strong class="text-white/80">Fission and branching as design opportunities:</strong> Parfit’s thought experiments show that psychological continuity can branch. This opens the conceptual space for thinking about how one identity geometry can be deliberately extended into multiple rich future trajectories (maximizing causal entropy through branching possibilities).
						</li>
						<li>
							<strong class="text-white/80">What matters framing:</strong> On one influential Parfitian reading, practical concern can shift from strict numerical sameness to the quality and richness of psychological connections. This is compatible with an Identity Engineering aim of cultivating open, connected causal futures through conscious geometric work.
						</li>
						<li>
							<strong class="text-white/80">Reductionism strengthens designability:</strong> If there is no deep further fact of personal identity, then the project of consciously designing and maintaining psychological continuity becomes even more central and legitimate.
						</li>
					</ul>
					<p class="mt-6">
						<strong class="text-white/80">Differentiation:</strong> Parfit is a major analytic reductionist voice in dialogue with Locke and Hume. Even where identity is not treated as a deep further fact, psychological continuity remains practically significant. Identity Engineering adds an intervention layer: deliberate work on strengthening, extending, and curving these relations.
					</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="border-t border-white/10 bg-white/[0.015] px-6 py-16">
			<div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl space-y-8 text-lg leading-relaxed text-white/55">
				<div>
					<div class="mb-2 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">Sources</div>
					<ul class="space-y-2 text-base text-white/50">
						<li>
							Primary: Derek Parfit, <em class="text-white/75 not-italic">Reasons and Persons</em> (1984), especially Part III on personal identity; see also Parfit, <a href="https://doi.org/10.2307/2184309" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-white/70 underline decoration-white/25 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white hover:decoration-white/50">“Personal Identity” (1971)</a>.
						</li>
						<li>
							Overview: <a href="https://plato.stanford.edu/archives/spr2026/entries/identity-personal/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-white/70 underline decoration-white/25 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white hover:decoration-white/50">Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy (Spring 2026 archive): Personal Identity</a> (Parfit sections).
						</li>
						<li>
							Ethics context: <a href="https://plato.stanford.edu/archives/spr2026/entries/identity-ethics/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-white/70 underline decoration-white/25 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white hover:decoration-white/50">Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy (Spring 2026 archive): Personal Identity and Ethics</a>.
						</li>
					</ul>
				</div>
				<div>
					<div class="mb-2 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">Related</div>
					<p>
						Parfit is the major late-20th-century analytic anchor. He radicalizes the empiricist tradition (Locke, Hume) while providing a precise framework for thinking about what actually matters in identity and survival. This anchor strengthens the justification for deliberate geometric work on psychological continuity and the extension of the Identity Stem into rich future trajectories.
					</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="border-t border-white/10 px-6 py-14">
			<div class="mx-auto flex max-w-3xl flex-col gap-4 text-sm sm:flex-row sm:items-center sm:justify-between">
				<a href="/foundations" class="text-white/50 transition hover:text-white/80">← All foundations</a>
				<div class="flex flex-wrap gap-x-6 gap-y-2">
					<a href="/ontology" class="text-white/50 underline decoration-white/20 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white/80 hover:decoration-white/40">Ontology</a>
					<a href="/blog" class="text-white/50 underline decoration-white/20 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white/80 hover:decoration-white/40">Blog</a>
					<a href="/framework" class="text-white/50 underline decoration-white/20 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white/80 hover:decoration-white/40">Framework</a>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>
	</main>
</Layout>
